Project Plan: Full-Internet News Search & Reliability Analyzer
1. Project Overview
Build a web application where users can search any topic and receive news results from across the entire internet. The app will:

Search the whole web using multiple news APIs + general web search

Categorize results into "Reliable" (main view) and "Unreliable" (dropdown)

Show all sources with transparency (domain, date, reliability score)

Download current news as .md or .pdf

Return to home view with trending topics

2. Key Requirement: "Search All Over the Internet"
To achieve true full-internet search, your backend must aggregate from multiple sources simultaneously:

Search Type	Sources	Coverage
News APIs	NewsAPI.org, GNews, TheNewsAPI, NewsData.io	Major news outlets worldwide
General Web Search	DuckDuckGo, Google (via API), Bing, Brave	Blogs, forums, independent sites
Archives	Internet Archive, Chronicling America	Historical/archived news
Implementation approach:

Use smart API switching to try multiple APIs when one hits rate limits

Combine results and remove duplicates by URL

Fallback to DuckDuckGo search for queries that return few news results

3. Reliability Scoring System
Core Logic
Each domain is checked against a reliability database before displaying results.

Option A: Use existing database (recommended)

NewsGuard provides comprehensive trustworthiness ratings for thousands of sources

Covers US, France, Italy, Germany, Canada, and expanding

Includes political orientation and topic classifications

Option B: Build your own

Start with a curated JSON list of 200+ domains

Allow user feedback to improve ratings over time

Reliability Scale
Score	Label	Example Domains
4.0–5.0	Very Reliable	Reuters, AP, BBC
3.0–3.9	Mostly Reliable	NYT, WSJ, The Guardian
2.0–2.9	Mixed/Opinion	BuzzFeed, HuffPost
1.0–1.9	Unreliable	Infowars, NaturalNews
0.0–0.9	Satire/Fake	The Onion
Display Rules
Main results area: Only sources with score ≥ 3.0

Dropdown: All sources with score < 3.0, clearly labeled as "Unreliable / Unverified"

Every card: Shows source name, domain, reliability badge, date, and snippet

